Fix AOT compatibility warnings in the project at `/tmp/sv-eb7c111dbc9e4e38ad75c31565b1c62a/before/`. Make the following specific changes:

## 1. Fix ArmEnvironment.cs (line 80)
Replace `JsonSerializer.Serialize(this)` in `ToString()` with manual JSON writing:

```csharp
public override string ToString()
{
    using var buffer = new System.IO.MemoryStream();
    using (var writer = new Utf8JsonWriter(buffer))
    {
        writer.WriteStartObject();
        writer.WriteString("Endpoint", Endpoint.ToString());
        writer.WriteString("Audience", Audience);
        writer.WriteString("DefaultScope", DefaultScope);
        writer.WriteEndObject();
    }
    return BinaryData.FromBytes(buffer.ToArray()).ToString();
}
```

Make sure the file has `using System.Text.Json;` (it should already).

## 2. Fix ArmClientOptions.cs (line 52)
Replace `JsonSerializer.Deserialize<Dictionary<string, Dictionary<string, JsonElement>>>(span)` with `JsonDocument` parsing.

Current code around line 52:
```csharp
var span = BinaryData.FromStream(stream).ToMemory().Span;
var allProfile = JsonSerializer.Deserialize<Dictionary<string, Dictionary<string, JsonElement>>>(span);
var armProfile = allProfile["resource-manager"];
```

Replace with:
```csharp
using var profileDoc = JsonDocument.Parse(BinaryData.FromStream(stream));
var armProfile = profileDoc.RootElement.GetProperty("resource-manager");
```

Then update the loop that follows. Currently it's:
```csharp
foreach (var keyValuePair in armProfile)
{
    var namespaceName = keyValuePair.Key;
    var element = keyValuePair.Value;
    foreach (var apiVersionProperty in element.EnumerateObject())
    {
```

After the change, `armProfile` is a `JsonElement`, so update to:
```csharp
foreach (var keyValuePair in armProfile.EnumerateObject())
{
    var namespaceName = keyValuePair.Name;
    var element = keyValuePair.Value;
    foreach (var apiVersionProperty in element.EnumerateObject())
    {
```

Read the full method first to understand the loop body before making changes. Only the outer loop variable access needs adjustment (`.Key` → `.Name`, `.Value` stays the same).

## 3. Fix Extensions/ArmClientBuilderExtensions.cs (line 30)
The method `AddArmClient<TBuilder, TConfiguration>` calls `builder.RegisterClientFactory<ArmClient, ArmClientOptions>(configuration)` which is marked with `[RequiresUnreferencedCode]` and `[RequiresDynamicCode]`. Add these attributes to the method:

```csharp
[RequiresUnreferencedCode("Binding strongly typed objects to configuration values is not supported with trimming. Use the Configuration Binder Source Generator (EnableConfigurationBindingGenerator=true) instead.")]
[RequiresDynamicCode("Binding strongly typed objects to configuration values requires generating dynamic code at runtime, for example instantiating generic types. Use the Configuration Binder Source Generator (EnableConfigurationBindingGenerator=true) instead.")]
```

Make sure to add `using System.Diagnostics.CodeAnalysis;` to the file.

## 4. Fix ArmOperation.cs - Add DynamicallyAccessedMembers to T
The `IsResource<T>()` method at line 96 uses `typeof(T).GetConstructor(...)` and `Activator.CreateInstance(typeof(T), ...)` which require `[DynamicallyAccessedMembers]` on the generic parameter T.

Add the constraint to the `IsResource<T>()` method:
```csharp
private static bool IsResource<[DynamicallyAccessedMembers(DynamicallyAccessedMemberTypes.PublicConstructors | DynamicallyAccessedMemberTypes.NonPublicConstructors)] T>() where T : notnull
```

Then also add it to the two public methods that call `IsResource<T>()`:

For `Rehydrate<T>`:
```csharp
public static ArmOperation<T> Rehydrate<[DynamicallyAccessedMembers(DynamicallyAccessedMemberTypes.PublicConstructors | DynamicallyAccessedMemberTypes.NonPublicConstructors)] T>(ArmClient client, RehydrationToken rehydrationToken, ArmClientOptions options = null) where T : notnull
```

For `RehydrateAsync<T>`:
```csharp
public static async Task<ArmOperation<T>> RehydrateAsync<[DynamicallyAccessedMembers(DynamicallyAccessedMemberTypes.PublicConstructors | DynamicallyAccessedMemberTypes.NonPublicConstructors)] T>(ArmClient client, RehydrationToken rehydrationToken, ArmClientOptions options = null) where T : notnull
```

Add `using System.Diagnostics.CodeAnalysis;` to the file.

## 5. Fix GenericOperationSource.cs - Add DynamicallyAccessedMembers to T

The class `GenericOperationSource<T>` uses `ModelReaderWriter.Read(response.Content, typeof(T))` and `Activator.CreateInstance(typeof(T), ...)` which need `[DynamicallyAccessedMembers]`.

Change the class declaration:
```csharp
internal class GenericOperationSource<[DynamicallyAccessedMembers(DynamicallyAccessedMemberTypes.PublicConstructors | DynamicallyAccessedMemberTypes.NonPublicConstructors)] T> : IOperationSource<T>
```

The file already has `using System.Diagnostics.CodeAnalysis;`.

## 6. Fix ManagedServiceIdentity.Serialization.cs

In `Write` method (line 31): Replace `JsonSerializer.Serialize(writer, ManagedServiceIdentityType, jOptions)` 
The `ManagedServiceIdentityType` has a custom `ManagedServiceIdentityTypeV3Converter` that writes the "type" property name and value. The converter's `Write` method does:
```csharp
writer.WritePropertyName("type");
if (model == ManagedServiceIdentityType.SystemAssignedUserAssigned)
    writer.WriteStringValue("SystemAssigned,UserAssigned");
else
    writer.WriteStringValue(model.ToString());
```

So to replace the serialize call, inline the converter logic. When `jOptions` is null (no custom converter), we need to handle both cases. But since the converter is always applied (via `[JsonConverter]` attribute or via options), we need to replicate this logic.

Replace `JsonSerializer.Serialize(writer, ManagedServiceIdentityType, jOptions);` with:
```csharp
ManagedServiceIdentityTypeV3Converter.WriteManagedServiceIdentityType(writer, ManagedServiceIdentityType);
```

BUT - we need to add a static method to the converter. Actually, a simpler approach: just inline the logic:
```csharp
writer.WritePropertyName("type"u8);
if (ManagedServiceIdentityType == ManagedServiceIdentityType.SystemAssignedUserAssigned)
{
    writer.WriteStringValue("SystemAssigned,UserAssigned");
}
else
{
    writer.WriteStringValue(ManagedServiceIdentityType.ToString());
}
```

In the same file, line 49: Replace `JsonSerializer.Serialize(writer, item.Value, jOptions);`
`item.Value` is a `UserAssignedIdentity` which implements `IJsonModel<UserAssignedIdentity>`. Replace with:
```csharp
writer.WriteObjectValue(item.Value, ModelSerializationExtensions.WireOptions);
```

In the same file, line 206: Replace `type = JsonSerializer.Deserialize<ManagedServiceIdentityType>($"{{{property}}}");`
This deserializes a JSON string like `{"type":"SystemAssigned"}` into a `ManagedServiceIdentityType`. The converter reads the "type" property value. Inline the logic:
```csharp
var typeValue = property.Value.GetString();
if (string.Equals(typeValue, "SystemAssigned,UserAssigned", StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase))
{
    type = ManagedServiceIdentityType.SystemAssignedUserAssigned;
}
else
{
    type = new ManagedServiceIdentityType(typeValue);
}
```

In the same file, line 218: Replace `JsonSerializer.Deserialize<UserAssignedIdentity>(property0.Value.GetRawText())` with:
```csharp
UserAssignedIdentity.DeserializeUserAssignedIdentity(property0.Value)
```

Use the `edit` tool for all changes. Read each file first before editing if needed to understand context.

